data.name: label2.Text
data.value:
Our map editor, often called 'Forge Mode' (from Halo), is an in-game utility we designed to (literally) build the school. We have included it in our full release of the game for your personal enjoyment. That, and it would be pretty hard to delete it all now.
It may be tricky to learn at the begining, but once you get the hang of Forge Mode, you'll have the power of God in your hands. Or at least a virutal God.

data.name: textBox1.Text
data.value:
One unit in the game is about one foot. This is a very rough approximation
Decimal values are valid throughout the program. "Boolean" refers to a value that can only be true or false
A "string" is a series of keyboard characters that usually form a word Examples: dog, cat, 343, a23, etc
All 3D "vectors" or "coordinates" are in a Cartesian (x,y,z) form +Imagine that the X and Z directions are in the plane of the ground +The Y direction is always perpedicular to this plane (gravity pulls you down)
Every object has a set list of properties: +Name: Player-declared name for an object +Location: 3D vector that represents a model's current position in the world +Rotation: 3D vector represents the rotation of an object on 3 axes (in degrees) +Moveable: boolean that controls if the object can be moved or not +PickUpable: boolean that controls if the object can be picked up or not +Bounciness: 0 to 1 (low to high) decimal value that represents how bouncy an object is +Levitating: boolean that controls if this object will fall due to gravity or stay in place +Stamp: function that makes a copy of the object at the current location
Special objects have the same basic properties as regular objects, but they also have a set of unique properties
(*Note: it is not recommended to change the Name property on special objects. This may or may not disable the objects special ability; it depends on who in the development team you ask)
Doors: +Doors allow one room file to open up another room file at a specific door +Use # and another string after door file name to specify which door to load the other room from +DoorSender: name of this door (name that is being sent to the other doors) +DoorReciever: name of the door that will be opened from another room (name that is being recieved by this door)
Computers: +Computers do not have any special properties. They just run the in-game console
Walls: +Dimensions: 3D Vector representing the dimensions of the wall +Color: Red, Blue, Green (RGB) value of the wall's color. When selected, values can only be changed by using pressing the T or the A key. The T key will open a color selection tool while the A key will allow the player to choose an alpha value (wall's transparency)
+Any and all bugs are inherently Nick's fault
